<div style="font-family:Tourmaline;">Phenomenon 499, known colloquially as 'REDACTION' or 'INFORMATION EIGENGRAU', is a major phenomenon that manifests for any and all forms of documentation.
==<div style="font-family:Extreme Glitch;"><span class="textfillpic">Description</span></div>==
----{{Blurimage|file=Redaction example.png|caption=An example of Phenomenon 499. [[Level 35|>File:Level35.bck]]}}{{Blurimage|file=Redaction Example 2.png|caption=A second example of Phenomenon 499. <br>[[Level 229|>File:Level229.bck]]}}Phenomenon 499 affects all forms of documentation, both physical and digital, regardless of how much security they have. The phenomenon cannot function under direct line of sight of the document if it is physical. However, when a document is under constant manual surveillance, the surveyors will gain an urge to look away, eventually overriding whatever training or instructions they may have. Digital surveillance equipment will lapse for roughly one frame, during which the phenomenon takes place. Digital documentation is edited in sync with any other physical copies. Digital documents can be changed by the phenomenon at any time.
<br>
The phenomenon will pick random pieces of information, ranging from dates and names to entire paragraphs, and obscure it in some way. On digital documents, it will usually redact the sections or password-protect them, and on physical documentations it will in some way become unintelligible, whether through redaction or physical wear-and-tear. The phenomenon seems to not be limited to any one piece of information, and can affect the same piece of documentation multiple times, leading to certain older documents being completely redacted.
<br>
When encountering affected information, wanderers will commence an overwhelming desire to locate the original information. This typically manifests as an urge to sort through separate documents to piece together the missing information, as well as interrogating the original writers of the documents to find more info. However, this often spirals into violent actions in an attempt to discover the legitimate information. This causes severe and harmful mental effects to the affected.
<br><br>
Given a prolonged period of time in this state, the affected individual's mind will begin degrading, with neural pathways seemingly disintegrating into thin air. Memories held by the wanderer will begin to have the document prevalent in them, motivating them to search further. This degradation slowly spreads to more important parts of the brain, which when left unchecked can cause fatality. The deceased wanderer's brain activity will continue for a long amount of time not dissimilar to that of [[Phenomenon 35#Stage V - Medium Mortis|Stage V Roth Syndrome]], even if severe damage is sustained. This prolonged brain activity will cease est. 1 year after death.
<br>
==<div style="font-family:Extreme Glitch;"><span class="textfillpic">Preventative Measures</span></div>==
----The former primary preventative measure for this phenomenon is the existence of multiple duplicates of the same document. However, for unknown reasons, duplicate documents are now replicating the exact same redactions that the originals had, leaving this method unreliable at best. It is advised to keep documents in multiple formats, such as audio, digital, manual and oral. Another method is to drink large quantities of [[Object 1|Almond Water]] and resist all urges to research further. After roughly three weeks of this routine, the phenomenon will stop affecting the wanderer, though it will restart if they encounter affected information. It is advised not to interrupt those affected by the phenomenon, as you will only risk getting yourself hurt.
<br>
==<div style="font-family:Extreme Glitch;"><span class="textfillpic">See Also</span></div>==
----
*[[Phenomenon 35|Roth Syndrome]], phenomenon believed to in some way be connected to Phenomenon 499.
*[[Phenomenon 42|Sensory Isolation]], a common symptom of the later stages of the phenomenon.
*[[Phenomenon 366|Crimson Trauma]], a common symptom of the later stages of the phenomenon.

